A central tenet of mechanistic interpretability is that meaningful features are represented by directions in the embedding space. However, the

div.div:
Residual stream
= 3 768
(-dimensional latent space)
Carries the input embeddings forward to each sublayer of the model, with each sublayer applying an “edit.” The residual stream is the central communication channel in a transformer; “it doesn't do any processing itself and all layers communicate through it” (and only through it). Each attention and MLP sublayer “reads” in the residual stream (via a linear projection), performs some computation, and then “writes” some result back to the residual stream (via element-wise addition). The residual stream is only modified by addition with these sublayer outputs; it is in essence a series of end-to-end skip connections.
This linear, additive structure has several important consequences. First, during back propagation, addition preserves the full magnitude of the gradient. This allows the gradient to flow backwards through the residual stream to every layer during training, preventing “vanishing gradients” and making it feasible to train very deep models.
Second, during forward inference, the residual connections help prevent the input embeddings and early layer outputs from being overly degraded through repeated transformations. This means that the original embeddings, as well as early layer outputs, can generally be accessed by later sublayers. This persistence is enhanced by the use of subspaces: earlier sublayers can communicate to specific later sublayers (or even specific later attention heads) by “writing to different subspaces of the residual stream.” A single attention head might “send different information to different layers by storing it in different subspaces.” [Due to the high dimensionality of the embedding space?] it appears that “information persists in a subspace unless another layer actively deletes it.”
This persistence and the use of subspaces allows the model to optimize how information is pathed through the model. We can conceptualize transformers as implementing computational functions which correspond to particular paths: e.g., some function might go from an attention head in layer 2, through an MLP in layer 5, to an attention head in layer 8, and so on. [cite NN]
Each such path is free to use its own encoding. All of these encoded messages from one layer to another to another are layered on top of another in the residual stream. This makes the residual stream itself not a particularly tractable target for interpretability work. “Rather than analyze the residual stream vectors, it can be helpful to decompose the residual stream into all these different communication channels, corresponding to paths through the model.”
[Further difficulty for interpreting the residual stream: The residual stream can be seen as the model's shared, working memory. It is “the only way that information can move between layers, and so the model needs to find a way to store all relevant information in there” (NN) Ergo, under high demand, and expect it to exhibit significant superposition.]

div.div: Transforms each input vector independently to have mean 0 and variance 1, then scales and shifts each component of the now-normalized vector by a learned scaling factor () and shifting factor (). (Each LayerNorm layer has a -length and which is applied component-wise.)

Purpose: The initial normalization promotes consistent distributions of input to a layer by reducing “covariate shift” (Ba et al., 2016), thereby stabilizing gradients and speeding up training. The parameterized scale and shift then return some flexibility to the model, allowing it to optimize the transformation for each layer.

Implications: In GPT-2, LayerNorm mediates every “read” of the residual stream (i.e., at the start of each attention or MLP sublayer, and before Unembed). Because LayerNorm is a non-linear transformation, it complicates interpretability, which prominent researchers have expressed frustration about.

In principle, the non-linearity in LayerNorm can perform useful computation, and it can even work as a general-purpose activation function. In practice within LLM architectures, it is an open question whether LayerNorm performs any “meaningful” computation or if it is merely an artifact of the training process. Attempts have been made to train more interpretable models without LayerNorm, and a recent preprint claims to have removed GPT-2's LayerNorm layers with fine-tuning with only minor performance degradation, suggesting it does not play a crucial role at inference time.

div.div: A learned lookup table mapping sequence positions to positional encodings. A challenge for the transformer architecture is that it is “order invariant”: although the token embeddings superficially appear to be stored in order, this ordering is not exposed to any of the model's computation. But for language, order matters.

div.style: text-align: left;
div.span: There are many approaches to adding position information (absolute or relative) to the token embeddings (or directly to the attention calculation). GPT-2 simply parameterizes it, allowing the model itself to figure out for itself how to represent sequence order. Each row of contains a learned “time signal” that is added to token embedding , thereby marking its position.
This means that the size of this matrix must be defined at training time, thereby fixing the maximum sequence length (“context length”) that the model can process: 1,024 for GPT-2.

div.div: Attention in transformer decoders is causal: each embedding can only attend to itself and prior embeddings in the sequence. For computational efficiency, this is typically implemented by a “masking” step after taking the dot product of all embedding pairs, but it displayed here conceptually, with each embedding only interacting with itself and its preceding embeddings. This, and the weighted sum below, are the only places in the model where embeddings interact.

Output weight matrix
For attention layer 1, head 1
= 64 768
Embeds the weighted-sum of the value projections for each token back to embedding space.
NB: This is typically implemented as a per-layer transformation rather than a per-head transformation, for computational efficiency. by taking the weighted-sum projection for each token position from each head (each a -dimensional vector), concatenating them to make a -dimensional vector, and then transforming this concatenation all at once with . Here, we take -sized slices of for each head. This is mathematically equivalent and provides a per-head output embedding that can be a locus of interpretation.
